  <section class="work">
    <div class="container">  
      <div class="row-fluid">
        <div class="col-md-9"> 
          <h2>Our Work</h2>
          <h3>See Well to Learn’s Vision 360⁰ employs an innovative, school-based approach to accurately detect preschoolers who have vision problems and ensure that those underserved children receive the care they need for vision correction so they can enter Kindergarten ready to learn.</h3>
          <p>Components of this program include:</p>
          <ol>
            <li>Vision screening performed by a certified vision screener at preschool sites, using advanced, scientifically validated screening technology</li>
            <li>Comprehensive eye exams for those children that fail the screening. Exams are performed by a licensed optometrist onboard the Eye Bus that returns to the school</li>
            <li>Connection to pediatric ophthalmology, if necessary</li>
            <li>Free prescription glasses for children that require them (including one replacement pair)</li>
            <li>Follow-up vision check for children that are prescribed glasses and are at higher risk for serious ongoing vision problems</li>
            <li>Continued support to school staff and parents of children that are prescribed glasses or other treatment</li>
          </ol>
          <p>In addition, SWTL addresses compliance issues, which are especially challenging in this age group.  Time is spent calling parents and teachers of those that are prescribed glasses to make sure that the child is wearing them, to address any concerns, and to give tips on how to get the child to comply with treatment. SWTL also holds fun events for children wearing glasses so that parents can meet and support each other, and children can see other children their age wearing glasses. The result is that teachers are reporting more children in their classrooms wearing glasses and becoming more engaged in activities.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
